s of foliage over which the rain may pour in torrents without weakening the resistance offered by their real and lasting happiness) hoisted, to keep them flying throughout the season, in the village streets, on the walls of the houses and in their gardens its silken banners, violet and white.”</p> <p>His remembrance of things past extended even to the sound of rainwater “dripping from our chestnut-trees, but I would know that the shower would only glaze and brighten the greenness of their thick, crumpled leaves, and that they themselves had undertaken to remain there, like pledges of summer, all through the rainy night.”</p> <p><br /></p>","wordcount":"256","commentCloseDate":"2016-08-18T20:30:14Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/4ytc4","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/366d749d9cb70209a9df8ed7eb776a49326e620e/0_0_3243_1946/500.jpg"},"tags":[{"id":"news/series/weatherwatch","type":"series","sectionId":"news","sectionName":"News","webTitle":"Weatherwatch","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/news/series/weatherwatch","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/news/series/weatherwatch","references":[],"description":"Our regular column investigating the stories behind the weather"},{"id":"science/meteorology","type":"keyword","sectionId":"science","sectionName":"Science","webTitle":"Meteorology","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/meteorology","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/science/meteorology","references":[]},{"id":"books/marcelproust","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Marcel Proust","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/marcelproust","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/marcelproust","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","type